    <h2 id=id7>Floor standing Speakers :</h2>
    <div id=id8>
     <div id=id9>Floor standing Speakers are loudspeakers in speaker enclosures specifically designed for professional audio production applications, <br/>
      such as recording studios, filmmaking, television studios, radio studios and project or home studios, where accurate audio reproduction<br/>
       is crucial. Among audio engineers, the term monitor implies that the speaker is designed to produce relatively flat (linear) phase and <br/>
       frequency responses. In other words, it exhibits minimal emphasis or de-emphasis of particular frequencies, the loudspeaker gives an <br/>
       accurate reproduction of the tonal qualities of the source audio ("uncolored" or "transparent" are synonyms), and there will be no relative<br/>
        phase shift of particular frequencies—meaning no distortion in sound-stage perspective for stereo recordings.

     </div>
     <div id=id10><img src="https://images.crutchfieldonline.com/ImageHandler/trim/350/265/products/2016/30/107/g107SiGS50-F.jpg"id=id11></div>
    </div>

        <h2 id=id7>Book Shelf Speakers :</h2>
        <div id=id8>
         <div id=id9>In the 1950s and 1960s, high quality home loudspeakers were exclusively large and floor-standing speaker enclosures, whereas <br/>
          small speaker cabinets had reputation of low price and low audio quality. However, beginning in the 1960s, some manufacturers began making <br/>
          more expensive, compact high fidelity speakers.[1] The demand for smaller speakers was from hifi enthusiasts who lived in small apartments,<br/>
           who did not have space for large speaker enclosures.<br/>
  
          Edgar Villchur, who along with partner Henry Kloss founded Acoustic Research, is generally credited with inventing bookshelf speakers.[2]<br/>
           Villchur's key innovation was an acoustic suspension (also called "sealed box") design, by which the woofer and other drivers were in <br/>
           separately enclosed chambers. The speaker drivers were stiffer and much smaller than the earlier ported designs.[2] The acoustic suspension <br/>
           design enabled the air in the sealed box to act like a spring, to help prevent excessive excursion. Advent, now defunct, was another early<br/>
            manufacturer of bookshelf speakers.
         </div>
         <div id=id10><img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c6/Ls3_5a.jpg/110px-Ls3_5a.jpg"id=id11></div>
        </div>
